# 📂 Spring Boot Docker Example Repository

Example repository used for demonstration:

```
https://github.com/ashokitschool/spring-boot-docker-app.git
```

---

# 📥 Step 1 — Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/ashokitschool/spring-boot-docker-app.git
```

---

# 📁 Step 2 — Navigate to Project Directory

```bash
cd spring-boot-docker-app
```

---

# ⚙ Step 3 — Build the Application

Compile the project and generate the JAR file.

```bash
mvn clean package
```

After successful build, the JAR file will be created in:

```
target/
```

Check the generated file:

```bash
ls -l target
```

Example output:

```
app.jar
```

---

# 🏗 Step 4 — Build Docker Image

Build a Docker image using the Dockerfile.

```bash
docker build -t sb-app .
```

Explanation:

| Option | Meaning |
|------|------|
| docker build | Creates a Docker image |
| -t sb-app | Image name (tag) |
| . | Current directory contains Dockerfile |

---

# ▶ Step 5 — Run Docker Container

Run the container from the image.

```bash
docker run -d -p 8080:8080 sb-app
```

Explanation:

| Option | Meaning |
|------|------|
| -d | Run container in background |
| -p 8080:8080 | Port mapping |
| sb-app | Image name |

### Port Mapping

```
Host Machine Port → Container Port
8080 → 8080
```

---

# 📜 Check Container Logs

After the container starts, check the logs.

```bash
docker logs <container-id>
```

Example:

```bash
docker logs 7f4a8b2d1c3e
```

Logs will show the **Spring Boot startup process**.

---

# 🌍 Access the Application

Once the container is running, access the application using:

```
http://localhost:8080
```

If running on a cloud VM:

```
http://<vm-public-ip>:8080
```

Example:

```
http://54.210.100.25:8080
```

---

# 🔄 Complete Workflow

```
Spring Boot Application
        ↓
mvn clean package
        ↓
app.jar generated
        ↓
Dockerfile
        ↓
docker build
        ↓
Docker Image
        ↓
docker run
        ↓
Docker Container
        ↓
Application running on port 8080
```

---

# ✅ Benefits of Dockerizing Spring Boot

✔ Consistent environment across machines  
✔ No need to install Java manually  
✔ Easy deployment to servers or cloud  
✔ Portable and scalable application deployment
